{{Infobox East Asian name |title=Munafuda |img=Munefuda.jpg |imgwidth=200px |caption=A {{ill|Munafuda|ja|棟札|12=draft|12=draft}} from the {{ill|Kuga Residence|ja|長島水辺のやすらぎパーク|12=draft|12=draft}}, showing the year Meiji 12 (1879).
|chinesetitle=上樑記牌 |chinese=上樑記牌 |tradchi=上樑記牌 |simpchi=上梁记牌
|japanesetitle=棟札 |kanji=棟札 |kana=むなふだ、むねふだ |hepburn=Munafuda, Munefuda }}
'''Munafuda''' (棟札, also read as ''Munehuda'') are plaques installed in elevated areas within structures like {{ill|shrines and temples|ja|寺社|1=Temples and Shrines|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|houses|ja|住宅|12=draft|12=draft}} to record and commemorate their construction or renovation.
== Overview ==
Typically, a munafuda is made from wood or copper and is nailed onto {{ill|ridge beams|ja|棟木|12=draft|12=draft}} or {{ill|rafters|ja|梁 (建築)|12=draft|12=draft}}. In some cases, the information is written directly on structural components, referred to as "beam inscriptions" (梁上銘), though their purpose is essentially the same.<ref>Yorisuke Numata, "Evolution of Munafuda," in *Archaeological Journal*, Vol. 8, Issue 7 (No. 222), March 1918.</ref>
The content on a munafuda typically includes the purpose of the construction or renovation, the date, the names of the builder(s) and sponsor(s), and other construction records. Some plaques are simple, while others feature intricate details or illustrations. Since munafuda are placed in locations not visible to the general public, they are often forgotten over time. They are sometimes rediscovered during demolition or repair projects.
The information on munafuda, despite occasional inaccuracies, serves as critical historical evidence, providing insights into the history and culture of a building or region. Many munafuda have been designated as cultural properties. The oldest known munafuda dates back to {{ill|Chūson-ji|ja|中尊寺|12=draft|12=draft}} in Iwate Prefecture, with an inscription from the third year of the Hōan era (1122).
== Munafuda in Literature ==
A reference to munafuda appears in the writings of Nichiren during the Kenji era: >"Regarding the matter of the munafuda, I have received the request and will pass it to this Lord Hōki. This inscription commemorates the construction of the Jeta Grove Monastery by the millionaire Sudatta. However, due to certain karmic causes, the millionaire faced fire disasters seven times, as he reported to the Buddha…" ([http://tidouji.la.coocan.jp/gosyo/sinnpenn/0902.pdf Ueno-dono Gosho])
== References ==
{{Reflist}}
== Further Reading == * Akiyama Kei, *Basic Research on Munafuda*, Iwata Shoin, February 2010.
